{TEXT -1 80 "Maple was NOT able to find all 5 linear factors for this \+
polynomial of degree 5." }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 31 "It onl
y found 2 linear factors." }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 
"" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 650 "In those cases where Maple did not find enough linear fa
ctors, there is a reason why Maple did not.  Maple makes an assumption
 that if the coefficients of a polynomial are all given exactly (as in
tegers or rational numbers [ratios of integer]), then you are only int
erested in finding exact factors (factors where the coefficients are i
ntegers or rational numbers).  The Fundamental Theorem of Algebra does
n't guarantee that the factors of  a polynomial will necessarily have \+
the same kind of coefficients as the polynomial, only the polynomial c
an be factored.  You can force Maple to report additional (approximate
) factors.  For example,  compare:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}
{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 10 "factor(h);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 
"" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*&,&%\"xG\"\"\"F&F&F&,&*$)F%\"\"#F&F&\"\"&!\"\"F&" }
}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 18 "factor(h,sqrt(5));" }}
{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*(,&%\"xG\"\"\"*$\"\"&#F&\"\"#F&F&,&F%
F&F'!\"\"F&,&F%F&F&F&F&" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "
" 0 "" {TEXT -1 52 "What is the difference?  The extra-term is called \+
a " }{TEXT 274 18 "field extension.  " }{TEXT -1 178 "Adding it tells \+
Maple to consider additonal factors where the coefficients are allowed
 to include elements from the field extension.  It is fairly clear fro
m the factoriztion of " }{TEXT 275 1 "h" }{TEXT -1 280 " all by itself
 that something involving  sqrt(5)  would have to be included.  Howeve
r, there are problems where there is not a obvious clue as to which sp
ecific field extension should be added.  If you are willing to accept \+
an appropriate solution, then using the field extension " }{TEXT 276 
4 "real" }{TEXT -1 179 " tells Maple to factor the polynomial using a \+
floating point approximation scheme.  For example, consider (here I am
 pretending I don't see that adding  sqrt(5) would be optimal):" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 
10 "factor(h);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*&,&%\"xG\"\"\"F&F&F
&,&*$)F%\"\"#F&F&\"\"&!\"\"F&" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 
0 15 "factor(h,real);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*(,&%\"xG\"\"
\"$\"+xz1OA!\"*F&F&,&F%F&$F&\"\"!F&F&,&F%F&$\"+xz1OAF)!\"\"F&" }}}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 91 "Finally, \+
the Fundamental Theorem of Algebra does not guarantee that a polynomia
